- Interworks is now shipping Interworks' T-Net rendering farm. This is a
  distributive rendering software package that runs on the company's
  Ethernet-based peer-to-peer network, ENLAN-DFS. (It will also support
  ScreamerNet systems.) T-Net will administer rendering multiple LightWave
  3D scenes among several machines. You can even identify specific frames
  to render. There are also provisions to adjust resolution, anti-aliasing
  level, raytracing options, etc.  right from the interface.
  There is extensive real-time information about rendering activity and
  statistics. T-Net will even send messages to alpha-numeric pagers on
  rendering status and problems. It is highly configurable as to who it
  should page in different situations as well as back up pagers to notify.
  T-Net also features the ability to remotely control any of the nodes
  from a single Amiga. It is very quick, though not as fast as really
  being on the remote machine.

  Interworks
  Professional Network Solutions
  43191 Camino Casillas
  Temecula, CA  92592-3714
  USA

  Phone: (909) 699-8120
  FAX:   (909) 699-8279
  EMail: info@iworks.com

- Blevins Enterprises offers VertiSketch, a 3D digitizing system for
  LightWave. The Model I10 has a robotic-like arm with a pointer on the 
  end. The device can triangulate the location of the tip of the pointer
  in 3D space. The points appear right in the LightWave Modeler display
  and the polygons are automatically built.
  All of the VertiSketch models being used had thread adhered to their
  surfaces forming a grid net. The pointer was then placed at intersecting
  lines on the grid. 

  Blevins Enterprises, Inc. (USA)
  Phone: (208) 885-3805

- Tahoe Software is selling QuickText version 2.0, yet another presentation
  system for the Amiga. The working environment of QuickText revolves 
  around layers of screens, on which you can place IFF pictures in up to
  HAM8 as backgrounds, add text, change colors, etc. A background animation
  can be substituted for the picture. Text handling exploits all of the 
  features of the standard Amiga font system (bold, italic, shadow, etc).
  Each text block is catalogued for easy editing after the fact. Variables
  can be used in text blocks and updated in real-time, most useful for 
  scoreboard displays.
  Screens can be added at will, with six standard wipe patterns for
  transitions. Each screen can have its own set of characteristics (high/
  low res, interlaced/non, and palette information). On-screen doodling is
  supported, and may be recorded for playback at a later time. A clock may
  be brought up on the screen and started/stopped at will.
  ARexx support is extensive, offering 61 commands for QuickText's more
  useful or repetitive features. QuickText can generate stereograms out
  of the present screen.
  QuickText is what it is-a program designed to work best in either a 
  kiosk-video board environment, or as an effect and title generator
  combined with a genlock (hence scoreboard and clock, and text scroll
  options).
  Priced at $60 US, Tahoe offers a demo disk and short demo tape. A demo
  version of QuickText is uploaded to AmiNet.

  Tahoe Software, Etc.
  PO Box 9236
  South Lake Tahoe, CA 96158
  USA

  Phone: (800) 939-4919 voice (US only)
  Phone: (916) 649-8935

