- The UK company Almathera Systems Limited is developing an update version
  1.2 to it's wonderful paint and image manipulation package Photogenics.
  Photogenics 1.2 retails at £59.95 and the upgrade from 1.1a to 1.2 costs
  only £15.00. You can purchase Photogenics 1.2 direct from Almathera. The
  new version 1.2 will be available in mid to late May and will feature:

  - Support for Harlequin and other Grafexa-style graphics cards to the new
    render-able boards
  - All new paint modes; colourise, gamma, mirage, jitter etc
  - GIO (graphic input/output) loaders, plug-ins
  - Scanner drivers
  - Support for plug-in type modules (effects)
  - PCHG (Palette Change Hires) support
  - A 'datatype.gio'
  - New .GIOs (TIFF, PCX, HAM6, RETINA, ProGrab24, etc...)
  - A new multiple-positionalbe-distortable-layers system
  - All new 150 pages manual.
  - The easy-to-use warper tool allows you to distort, stretch, bend and
    twirl parts of your image.
  - Photogenics can now print to any preferences supported printer.
    Photogenics also supports the STUDIO II colour management system for
    true 24-bit colour quality printouts
  - CyBERgraphics 24-bit painting; Photogenics can now paint in hi-colour
    (15/16 bit) and true colour (24-bit) directly with any graphics card 
    that supports the CyBERgraphics standard (CyBERvision 64, Picasso II,
    Retina Z3, etc..)
  - Transparency Gradients; you can now apply various transparency 
    gradients to rectangles, circles or other shapes you draw and give
    the direction of your transparency
  - Crop option; You can now crop an image to remove unwanted borders etc
  - For the end-user with non-AGA machines; the Ham6.gio/ShowHam6.gio and
    the 16 Colour preview.  Photogenics can now save and display standard
    Ham (or Ham-6)images as well as being run in a 16 colour preview
  - NewIcon support
  - Some improvement has been made to the Previews (Photogenics uses high
    quality dithering to get near 24-bit quality from a 256-colour display)
    and the Compose mode (You can use other paintmodes inside compose to 
    combine the two images in many different ways).
  - And much much more

