- There are a lot of falsk rumoures around about how fast a Pentium can
  render a pictures using LightWave. A Motorola 68060/50 MHZ is 20% to 30%
  faster than an Intel Pentium 90 MHZ. At the latest CeBIT they
  demonstrated it. An Amiga equipped with a Cyberstorm 68060/50 MHZ run
  LightWave faster (55 sec for the test frame) than the Pentium 90MHZ 
  (70 secs for the same frame).
  Imagine Amiga version 3.2 was also 30% faster on the 68060/50 MHZ
  Amiga compare to imagine running on an IBM PC clone equipped with an
  Intel Pentium 90 MHZ.

- A new version 40.46 of the Cybergraphics intuition WB Emulation system is
  now  released. The cybergraphics system was designed to define an
  independant graphics standard for graphics boards. The developers 
  included all their knowledge of about 3 years of gfx board software
  development (wb-emulation of visiona, domino, picasso and CyberVision64).
  CyberGraphics is based on hardware dependant monitor drivers and hardware
  independant libraries. This has some advantages: Bug fixes in the 
  workbench emulation or speed optimizations is of benefit for ALL gfx
  boards that are supported by the CyberGraphics system. There is no third
  like XpERT or Village-Tronic inbetween developers and users. That 
  guarantees bug fixes and continued development of the software in the
  future. CyberGraphics allows using of 15/16/24 screens independant of the
  used color model. You are able to use the cybergraphics.library functions
  to modify this screens. At the time of this writing there are drivers for
  Maxon Cinema,Real 3D, ADPro, AmaxIV, PhotoWorx, Emplant, ImageFX and 
  Photogenics available. There is also a picture viewer called CyberView
  which can be found on AmiNet. Cybergraphics is the nicest, most promising
  RTG systems the Amiga has ever had. Because CyberGfx runs on nearly ALL 
  gfx cards floating around, you'll get much more support for drivers. 
  Applications using CyberGfx are raising, begining with ShapeShifter.
  Cybergraphics is not only a card-independent system (allowing one product
  to work on a variety of different graphics cards) but it is actually 
  significantly faster than the hardware specific drivers provided with
  most graphic cards. Cybergraphics is what EGS should have been - a FAST
  and simple extension to the standard Amiga libraries to allow programs to
  be converted simply to take advantage of 24-bit graphics, and still 
  maintain standard system compatibility with the same executable code.
  Support for Retina Z2, A2410, and Merlin graphic board are planed for a
  future version. Cybergraphics currently features:

  - Stable Workbench emulation
  - Dragable screens
  - No chipmem required for screen display
  - Modular design, it is possible to use multiple (and different) gfx 
    boards at one time
  - CyberGraphics based vilintuisup.library. As long as there exist not
    much cybergraphics 15/16/24 bit applications the old picassoII drivers
    may be used.
  - Uses cirrus blitter for plane to chunky conversion
  - The current version supports the following graphic board:
    - CyberVision 64
    - Picasso II (unsegmented mode)
    - GVP Spectrum
    - Piccolo Z2/Z3
    - Domino
    - Retina Z3
      Much better software that Macrosystems RetinaEmu version 2.3.
      Supports screen dragging enabled, screenmodes support etc. Support
      for Retina Blitter is comming with the next version of Cybergraphics.
    - Piccolo SD-64

  A demo version of this excellent package me be downloaded from AmiNet.
  Priced at $40 US this package me be ordered directly from:

  Europe/Africa/Aisa/Australia/Antarctia distribution
  
  Frank Mariak   
  Klosterstr. 7  	
