- A new version 1.5 of InfraRexx and a new version 3.1 of InfraJoy is now
  released. The InfraRexx software along with the InfraJoy hardware serve
  as an ARexx-Infrared interface, that adds the function of an infrared 
  remote controller to your Amiga, and more. With the software and hardware
  you can:

  - Control external audio/video devices via ARexx commands.
  - Control Amiga programs via a common remote control unit.
  - Learn and edit new remote control infrared commands.

  For example you can control a moduleplayer via your compact disc player
  remote control unit. Or, control your video tape recorder via a graphic
  user interface or an ARexx script.

  The main features are:

  - Seperate editor (with learner) and ARexx host commodity.
  - Multitasking-friendly infrared sampling monitor, with very
  - low system overhead during monitoring; can also be disabled.
  - Font-sensitive, style-compliant graphic user interface.
  - Supports localization under Workbench 2.1 (or better).
  - Uses 3.x functions and gadtools features if present.
  - Lowcost hardware for joystickport, with optional throughput.
  - Uses the Amiga Installer Utility to install onto (hard)disk.

  The new version 1.5 features:

  - Added some user requested features. Removed reported bugs.
  - Swedish language catalog included.
  - Completer codesets. Added JVC codeset.
  - Included RexxEvent; links ARexx commands to input events.

  The freeware software is downloadable from AmiNet.

  EMail: leon@stack.urc.tue.nl
  EMail: jeroens@stack.urc.tue.nl

- Stefan Osowski's Schatztruhe is now shipping 2 new disks:

  - The Beauty of Chaos. This CD contains 507 fractals from the
    Mandelbrot set, complete with the formula used for each. Every
    fractal is rendered in three resolutions (640x400, 1024x768, and
    1140x890), all 256 color GIFs. In addition, 20 of the best ones are
    packaged as 24-bit TIFFs. The CD comes with considerable background
    information on fractals, including the theory behind their existance
    and the method used to generate them, not to mention the triple-
    platform viewers on the disc.

  - The Light Works CD. The disc is comprised of a great number of 
    prerendered scenes and animations, as well as objects in Cinema4D,
    Reflections, and Imagine To facilitate dabblers, demo versions of
    Cinema4D and Reflections are included. The collection is primarily
    the work of Tobias Richter, famous for his Star Trek renders.

