- An all new version 2.0 of Q-Blue, the popular offline mail reader for
  Amiga, by Paul Kienitz is now released to the Aminet.
  Q-Blue has long been the leading offline mail reader for Amiga computers,
  and version 2.0 represents a very substantial improvement over Q-Blue 1.0
  , the last official release. It handles both Blue Wave mail and QWK mail
  packets. It requires AmigaDOS 2.04 or newer. Q-Blue 1.0 is still
  available for those using older AmigaDOS versions.  But Q-Blue's strength
  has always been in how it handles the basics. Its user interface sets a
  standard for clarity and efficiency, it has gained a reputation for
  dependability and robustness even in early versions, and the thorough 136
  page user manual, noted as one of the best written of its kind, is now 
  clearer and better organized than ever. Some of the features that put
  Q-Blue 2.0 ahead of the competition include:

  - Full support for Fido netmail even with QWK packets
  - Configuration options that can be set differently for different BBSes
  - Remembers your place in a packet when you close and reopen it
  - You can copy text to the system clipboard with the mouse, and...
  - Paste from the clipboard into any string gadget
  - Run multiple processes safely and with no inconvenience
  - Messages can be sorted according to thread links
  - Support for PCBoard 15.x long subject lines with QWK mail
  - Conversion of ANSI-cluttered messages into clear readable text
  - A powerful word search function that can be used in any scrolling
      list window as well as on the text or header info of messages
  - A "twit filter" with options for finely selective filtering
  - Quoting for replies that knows how to reformat paragraphs to a
    user-settable margin before adding ">" markers along the left edge (try
    it, and soon any offline reader without this feature will drive you
    crazy!)
  - More sophisticated text editor support than other offline readers, with
    sections in the manual on taking maximum advantage of the special 
    features of popular editors like CygnusEd and TurboText
  - Automatically keeps backups of old reply packets
  - You can write messages to upload without any downloaded mail packet
  - Full ability to move, re-edit, delete, and undelete your replies, reload
    unfinished reply packets, and flip instantly between a reply and the
    message it's responding to
  - QWK netmail support now handles the MKQWK door
  - The window that lists available mail packets tells you how much of each
    packet has already been read, and has a file delete option
  - A "Reply to addressee" command
  - A "stealth" mode that suppresses identifying brag lines at the ends of
    messages (for registered users only)
  - Several improvements to the tagline feature, including a sequential use
    option
  - Support for high resolution video modes
  - Word search can filter previous search results with new criteria
  - Search "hits" in message text are visually highlighted
  - Tagline and signature-block support built in
  - Customizable headers on quoted messages ("John said to Mary...")
  - "Carbon copy" function with its own customizable header
  - It can now display messages 8000 lines long
  - Workbench AppIcon and commodities-style popkey
  - Single-key command to append messages to a preselected text file
  - The twit list can now restrict exclusions to specified message areas
  - Load configuration files even while a mail packet is open
  - "BBS Information" window with useful facts about the mail packet and 
    the BBS it came from

  The demo version of Q-Blue may be downloaded from AmiNet.

