- The UK company Almathera Systems Limited has just released an update
  version 1.1 to it's wonderful paint and image manipulation package
  Photogenics. The new version features:
  - Toolbar Changes
    - Smear
      Smear is a new powerful effect. When selected, the standard drawing
      options will smear the picture rather than applying a paint effect.
      Unlike other paint effects (eg. Negative) Smear does not use the
      standard system of operation where you can rub-out your work with the
      right mouse button. Both buttons do the same during smear. If you 
      have undo enabled you can use the Undo option from the menu to undo
      the LAST APPLIED smear operation. As smear affects the 24-bit data
      directly make sure you have a back-up of your image (either by 
      cloning the buffer or by saving to disk) before you start using
      Smear! Smear uses the current brush, so different effects can be
      used with other brush types like Chalk Pastel.
    - Colour Picker.
      Previosly this had no image.
  - Blur Paint Layer
    A new option has been added to the Alpha/Paint Layer menu called 'Blur
    Paint Layer'. This option will 'blur' the edges of the selected paint
    (without needing to fix it). If you draw a solid shape like a filled
    circle it normally has sharp, unnatural edges. By choosing this option
    the edges of this (and any other unfixed paint) are blurred so they 
    will blend into the background.
  - PCD.gio
    You can now load Photo .PCD files directly into Photogenics. Only the
    lowest three resolutions in .PCD (192x128, 384x256, and 768x512)
    are currently supported. This .GIO file loads and can automatically
    detect .PCD files
  - Close Workbench
    A new option to the settings menu, allows you to close workbench. 
    Select 'Close Workbench' if you are running short of memory.
  - Tolerance Fill
    This has been renamed 'Fill Similar'.
  - Colours Window
    If you press the 'Colours' button in the palette requester, you can
    now access the Colours window.  This lets you create spreads of
    colour, and also lets you see what palettes were saved with any images
    you may have loaded.
  - Greyscale
    The greyscale paintmode now has more options. Previously it had two
    different methods of calculating a greyscale picture. Now it has no
    less than eleven: Video Weighted, Simple Average, Brightest, Darkest,
    Median, Red Filter, Green Filter, Blue Filter, Cyan Filter, Magenta
    Filter, Yellow Filter
  - Brushes
    Four new brush types have been added to the program:
    - BallPen: Simulates a ballpoint ink pen. Like real pens the colours
               mix differently to normal paint.
    - Calligraphy: A simple angled nib calligraphy marker.
    - MarkerPen: Simulates a thick marker pen. Colour mixing works in a
               similar way to BallPen.
    - SprayCan: Spray can works like the airbrush but has a higher 
                pressure and defaults to continuous mode. Useful for
                highlighting areas for image processing.
  - Clock and Memory Display
  - Opalvision
    There are now two Opalvision displayers included Opal_Low and Opal_
    High. These replace the single displayer previously found in the
    program.
  Almathera Systems Limited
  Southerton House
  Boundary Business Court
  92-94 Church Road
  Mitcham, Surrey
  CR4 3TD
  ENGLAND
  Phone: (081) 687 0040
  Fax:   (081) 687 0490
  EMail: almathera@cix.compulink.co.uk
 
- We just recieved a fax from Advanced Systems & Software, AS&S, Germany,
  the maker of CyberVision and CyberStorm 68060 for the Amiga. The Amiga 
  4000 version of the CyberStorm is shipping now! The release date for 
  Amiga 3000 (YES, IT'S TRUE) is mid Feb 95! Also SOON! This baby sports a
  massive 85 Mips even in it's 50 MHZ (currently shipping). The CPU is 
  simply upgradable to the 80 Mhz version. The 80 Mhz 68060 will does apr.
  130 Mips! To get an idea how FASSTTTTT this babies are consider that an
  Amiga 3000/ 25 MHZ 68030 does apr. 7-8 MIPS. A4000/25 MHZ 68040 does apr
  18-19 MIPS. CyberVision 64, the fastest Amiga graphic board sporting S3
  technology is also shipping now for all ZORRO-III Amiga. 
  Phase 5 digital products development team (developer of Cyber products)
  , Official Motorola Beta Site Developer, is a leading technological 
  developer in the AMIGA sector. This has already been demonstrated with
  products such as the Fastlane Z3 or the Blizzard Series.
  Here is complete release information for these 2 Cyber products:
  - CyberStorm Amiga accelerator system sporting 68060 CPUs from Motorala
    This util consists of several modules but each CyberStorm system 
    contains a Carrier Board, a CPU Module and a Memory Board. The CPU 
    module can be exchanged for another version at any time without having
    to change any of the other components.  This concept guarantees optimal
    access speed and the greatest possible performance at each CPU speed.
    The CyberStorm System is not linked to any particular type of CPU.
    Processor modules with other than 680x0 processors can be installed at
    any time, as long as they are supported by the Amiga operating system.
    Wherever the future of the Amiga may lead, you can be assured that the
    CyberStorm will keep apace of technological advances.
    - CyberStorm Carrier Interface Board
      Inserts into the 200 pin Amiga Fast-Slot and contains ports for the
      CPU Module, Memory Board and the I/O Module. Fully asynchronous 
      interface between the modules. Extremely fast programmable logic,
      selected A-Grade FCT circuit logic, high-class high density connector
      Slot for 68060 software Boot ROM (or Flash ROM) or Ethernet Boot ROM
      (used with the CyberStorm I/O Module) to boot up the computer from a
      network hard drive.
    - CyberStorm CPU Module:
      Optimally tuned to the processor used and its speed Prepared for CPU
      clock speeds up to 80 MHz. Active CPU cooling, uncoupled CPU voltage
      supply with 5 or 3.3 Volt Voltage control at 3.3 V for 68060 version.
      Bi-directional high speed buffering with expensive A-Grade FCT 
      switching logic 120 pin high density port for Second Level Cache 
      Module or other expansions.
    - CyberStorm Memory module
      Slots for 4 SIMM modules in 32 bit technology standard 72 pin modules,
      Sizes: 4, 8, 16 and 32 MByte per module, freely mixable, maximum
      configuration 128 MByte. Fully DMA capable memory, also supports 
      Zorro3 DMA access. Fast 2-1-1-1 Burst Mode access when reading and
      3-1-1-1 when writing at 25 MHz RAM speed with 60 or 70 ns RAM) 
      achieving data transmission greater than 50 MByte/sec measured or
      effective value) Independent of CPU clock speed.
      The asynchronous interface concept also applies to the memory: the
      bi-directional buffer logic allows the CyberStorm CPU asynchronous 
      access to the memory which operates at the AMIGA system speed of 
      25MHz. This principle makes the memory transparent to other system
      components which access it by DMA, and avoids possible problems that
      can arise with so-called local memory designs which, for example, are
      directly linked with a CPU clock.  There is no principle speed 
      disadvantage over designs which operate the memory at higher clock
      speeds, as 25MHz is the upper limit for memory access without wait
      cycles (even for 60ns fast D-RAMs), which is performed on the 
      CyberStorm in Burst Mode Access. With a data throughput that is 
      nearly independent of the processor frequency of up to 66.66 MB/s in
      Burst Mode Access even a CyberStorm System clocked at 25 MHz 
      demonstrates clear acceleration, especially when working with large
      amounts of data.
    - CyberStorm I/O Module (Optional)
      Fast SCSI-II interface with internal and external 50 pin SCSI 
      connector. Data transmission in the full address area using its own
      32 bit DMA channel, FIFO buffered, bandwidth >30 MB/s. Asynchronous
      to 7 MB/s, synchronous to 10 MB/s data transmission on the SCSI bus
      with minimal CPU loading. The know-how gained from developing the 
      Fastlane Z3 (the world's first 32 bit SCSI Controller for the Amiga)
      was used extensively in the design of the SCSI interface, which has
      mature driver and utility software amongst other features. Extensive
      software including CD-ROM Filesystem, dynamic caching software and 
      various SCSI Tools.
      10 MBit/s Ethernet controller. SANA driver for transparent linking to
      various network systems. High speed due to its FIFO buffered, 32 Bit
      DMA channel Coaxial (BNC) and Dsub15 ethernet connector (Thin Ethernet
      /Standard Ethernet). 
      Serial high-speed interface RS232 with 115kbaud, with its own FIFO 
      buffer has also been integrated in the I/O Module to guarantee 
      problem-free operation of fast serial devices without data loss.
    - CyberStorm Cache Module (Optional)
      No further information currently available.
    The CyberStorm CPU Module also offers another High Speed Connector with
    direct processor connection through which, for example, cache memory 
    and boards with second processors (e.g.  DSPs) or other high speed 
    expansions can be connected. All CyberStorm components are manufactured
    in Germany to the highest industrial quality in modern Fine Pitch SMD
    technology and are subjected to complete functionality test prior to
    delivery. A3000 and A4000T versions have limited modularity and 
    expansion capabilities.
  - CyberVision 64, ultrafast 64-bit graphic acceleration system for Amiga:
    The CyberVision 64 satisfies the most demanding requirements on 
    performance and system conformity because of its combination of an
    extremely fast 32 bit Zorro-3 interface, a 64 bit wide graphics 
    controller and exceptional software. Based on the highly integrated
    graphic chip Trio64 from the renowned manufacturers S3, which 
    integrates an expensive graphics processor, a complex 64 bit wide
    Blitter as well as a highly efficient 24 bit converter for D/A 
    conversion, the CyberVision 64 can offer a video band width of 135 MHz.
    It will, therefore, support a variety of resolutions in True Color, 
    High Color and 256 colours. The CyberVision 64 32 Bit Zorro3 interface
    is highly optimised and allows transmission rates from the AMIGA main
    memory to the graphic memory of up to 16 MByte/sec - an exemplary rate
    that sets new standards. Data transfers within the CyberVision 64 
    video memory are executed by the 64 Bit Blitter at speeds above 100
    MByte/sec, practically in an imperceptible amount of time, resulting
    in extremely fast shifting operations, for example. Another special
    feature of the CyberVision 64 is its hardware support of Planar-to-
    Chunky Conversion which, with Amiga graphics cards, often takes up most
    of the time required for emulation/representation of the Amigamodes.
    This hardware solution is some 6-8 times faster than typical software
    solutions which considerably accelerates the emulation and 
    representation of Amiga modes and especially the representation of 8
    Bit graphics. Complementing this efficient hardware is excellent driver
    software which fully utilises the performance of the card for unusual
    system conformities. The CyberVision 64 screen modes are installed via
    the CyberVision 64 monitor files, are available via normal ASL-
    Requester (e.g.  in screen mode in PREFS) as "normal" system 
    resolutions, and for common applications operating under OS3.0 or 3.1
    require no additional driver.
    The CyberVision 64 has an expansion bus through which additional cards
    such as JPEG or MPEG cards can directly access the fast video memory
    making the CyberVision 64 suitable for future developments. The
    combination of the attention that has been paid to necessary details,
    such as slipped through AMIGA video signal and integrated, loss-free 
    electronic switching, default-monitor-timing on system start-up or 
    simple expansion of the 2MB version to 4MB with common memory modules,
    with the usual high quality of phase 5 products will be able to satisfy
    even the most demanding user.
    Resolution Noninterlaced: up to 1280x1024 pixels in 8 bit, up to 
    800x600 pixels in 24 bit; Interlaced: up to 1600x1200 pixels in 8 bit,
    up to 1024x768 pixels in 24 bit. 135 MHz Video DAC Planar-to-chunky pixel
    conversion using special hardware (RoXXIer chip). Slip through Amiga
    signal with loss-free, electronic switching Digital video bus for optimal
    expansion (shared memory bus) with access to the video memory. System 
    local software with Workbench emulation, Support Library, linking via
    monitor files CyberVision 64 screen modes including standard Amiga
    resolutions).
  For ordering information please contact your Amiga dealer or:

  Advanced Systems & Software, AS&S, Germany
  Tel: (69) 5488130
  Fax: (69) 5481845
  
