- We are proud to include promised information about DraCo, the first
  real Amiga clone developed by MacroSystem GmbH Germany in this issue
  of AmyNews:
	DraCo fulfills the dream of an affordable, powerful, and professional
  video and graphics workstation. DraCo offers perfect quality animation
  recording, non-linear editing, and animation rendering. DraCo is not an
  Amiga.  But you can run most of the Amiga hardware and software 
  applications with astoundingly dramtic results. 
  DraCo is an Amiga OS compatible computer that doesn't use the Amiga
  custom chip set.  These chips are replaced with powerful software and
  hardware combinations.  The blitter, for example, is replaced by the 
  powerful NCR 53C720 chip which is used, for example, in the Warp Engine.
  DraCo is based around the Motorola 060 processor, UNIX and UNIX clone
  support are included as well. This workstatation is certainly the most
  powerful video and graphics computer in this price category. (priced in
  the same equipped A4000 range)
  Technical data:
  - Processor:  Motorola 68060
  - Operating System:  Amiga OS & various UNIX Systems
  - Case:  Full size tower
  - I/O:  Fast SCSI-II with NCR 53C720 & Parallel Port
  - Slots: Two DraCo direct 32 bit interfacws dedicated for the Retina
    BLT and VLab Motion. The retina is standard in every computer, the
    VLab motion is optional. Five Zorro II slots for boards like the 
    Toccata, Emplant, Ethernet, VLab Y/C, serial ports, additional 
    parallel ports, etc.
  - Drive: Triple speed CD ROM drive standard, other SCSI devices optional
  - Graphics:  DraCo Retina BLT with 120 Mhz pixel frequency and data rate
    of over 180MB/Second in 24 bit
  - Memory:  4MB standard, expandable to 128MB
  - Software Compatibility:  All system compatible programs that runs on
    graphics cards like the Retina will work.
  - Hardware Compatibility:  All hardware products that are custom chipset
    independent. This includes the Toccata, Emplant, etc.
 
- Todd Vierling announces that a gamma version 0.9.1 of AmiNIX, a new 
  implementation of BSD UNIX is now released. It runs on any 680x0 series
  processor, and does not require either an MMU or FPU. It does not have
  the superstrict protection that NetBSD or Linux have, and is not
  designed for that; AmiNIX is designed for UNIX compatibility on few-to-
  one-user systems and for restricted remote use (via rksh and the like).
  AmiNIX is an ``extension'' that gives UNIX ability to AmigaOS. The
  release version 1.0 is under development.
  EMail: amigagod@grove.ufl.edu
 
