- Peter Deane announces the release of the BBS program OzMetro version 2.0
  Key features for version 2.0:
  - Very easy to run setup program for initial configuration
  - Ability to recover online user after a reboot
  - Powerful "Amigatised" sysop maintenance program with menus, gadgets,
    etc
  - Fully configurable file areas with control over uploads, downloads and
    "listabilty" for every area
  - Abilith optional MicroWeave printing.
  Resolutions are selected by the Preferences density setting:
    Density 1       180x180
    Density 2       360x180
    Denisty 3       360x360
    Denisty 4       360x360, MicroWeave
    Denisty 5       720x720
    Density 6       720x720, MicroWeave
    Density 7       720x720, MicroWeave (identical to Denisty 6) 
  The driver implements horizontal and verical whitespace stripping, as
  well as Epson compression mode 2 ("TIFF v4.0 packbits mode") to minimize
  the amount of data that must be sent to the printer and improve printing
  speed. A beta tester reported speed on an Amiga 3000 comperable to that 
  of a 66MHz 486 with Epson's MS-Windows driver.
  The driver implements a very simple color correction for 720dpi modes to
  prevent them from printing excessively dark.  This gives results similar
  to other drivers on the same printer (for example, the PageStream 2.x 
  LQ2550C driver). "Endicor Technologies, Inc." is investigating a future
  update with improved color correction, which will provide more accurate
  colors and better gradation.
  Contact Endicor Technologies, Inc. at:
  P.O. Box 29000 #355
  San Antonio, TX 78229
  USA
  Internet:  info@endicor.com, sales@endicor.com
  Voice/Fax: 1-210-650-4988
 
- The US company Softwood is working on a new spreadsheet program for the
  Amiga. It will blow away anything out for the Amiga to date. Supposedly
  it will be on the scale of Excel. FinalCalc (FC) is a high-end spread-
  sheet that aims at providing the Amiga with something to compete with
  the top spreadsheets in the 'outside world'.
  Its main formula recalc engine has been written to be significantly more
  powerful than the current generation of spreadsheets.  The engine always
  does a 'natural' recalc.  i.e. formulas are evaluated in the order of 
  their inter-dependancies, no matter how complex, making sure that the
  result of a formula is correct.
  The recalc engine always runs in the _background_.  The user never waits
  for FC to recalculate.  You keep on editing cells while FC chugs along 
  in the background, catching up and updating the display as you work. 
  This is very smooth and has to be used to be believed.  Even with this,
  the recalc code itself is very fast anyway, recalculating only what has
  changed or needs to be recalculated, not the entire project.
  FinalCalc's user interface is designed to be both easy to use, and
  power-user friendly.  Everything is keyboard/hotkey driven as well as
  mouse driven. Almost every function, requester, feature can be 
  controlled from the keyboard without using the mouse.  The user 
  interface can come up on any screen mode and use any Amiga font, even
  changing the screen mode and/or the user font on the fly.
  FinalCalc supports multiple sheets per 'Project'.  (a project can 
  consist of 1 to 254 sheets, each containing a maximum of ZZZ (18277)
  columns and 65000 rows.)
  FinalCalc has very powerful printing features, great 2D and 3D graphs,
  more than 630 arexx/script commands, and tons of features.
 
- The WARP System, a Transputer System for the Amiga, from the US company
  Cybernetic, is now released. The specs for the WARP are very impressive.
  WARP basically allows you to load off cpu intensive tasks to Transputer
  boards using the Warp OS. You can add as many boards as you want to 
  your system, increasing performance proportionally.  The base board does
  around 50 Mips and installs in a Zorro slot.  The other boards (Warp 
  Twin 70 Mips, Warp Tripple 105 Mips) are then connected to the base 
  board. System comparisons to an Amiga 4000/40 are quite impressive, a
  render that take around 1 hour on an A4000/40, take around 50 seconds
  on a 1000 Mips Warp system. A Warp System adapted (rendering engine) 
  for Adspec's Aladdin 4D is available, others including Real3D and 
  Lightwave are to follow. Cybernetic also announces Cybernetica's 
  "Reality Prime Engine Series" of software, a system of modules designed
  to work initially with Warp System, and later with other software on a
  standard Amiga. These releases, each with the engine tag, will add a 
  host of options for 3D animators. The lineup is slated LighEngine (for
  ray-tracing and radiosity), Physics (for animation control), Paint (for
  image-processing, compositing and painting), Modeling, Animation, 
  Morphing, Particle, Sound, Video and more. The releases will be
  staggered.  The Light Engine and Cybernetica's Newton's Law (animation
  module for LightWave) have already been released.
 
